1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,483
Aligning large language models with human preferences

2
00:00:03,483 --> 00:00:08,957
has traditionally relied on Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback, or RLHF.

3
00:00:08,957 --> 00:00:14,430
While powerful, RLHF is a notoriously complex and unstable multi-stage process.

4
00:00:14,430 --> 00:00:16,918
First, we perform Supervised Fine-Tuning.

5
00:00:16,918 --> 00:00:21,895
Then, we train a separate reward model on pairwise comparisons.

6
00:00:21,895 --> 00:00:27,368
Finally, we optimize the policy using Proximal Policy Optimization, or PPO.

7
00:00:27,368 --> 00:00:30,354
This third stage is the bottleneck.

8
00:00:30,354 --> 00:00:33,837
It requires keeping four neural networks in

9
00:00:33,837 --> 00:00:36,325
GPU memory simultaneously: the policy,

10
00:00:36,325 --> 00:00:41,302
the reference model, the reward model, and the value network.

11
00:00:41,302 --> 00:00:44,287
Tuning hyper-parameters is a dark art,

12
00:00:44,287 --> 00:00:48,268
and training is highly sensitive to policy collapse.

13
00:00:48,268 --> 00:00:51,751
Is there a way to bypass this

14
00:00:51,751 --> 00:00:54,239
complexity and optimize preferences directly?

15
00:00:54,240 --> 00:00:57,222
To understand how we can simplify alignment,

16
00:00:57,222 --> 00:01:00,204
we must examine the mathematical foundation of

17
00:01:00,204 --> 00:01:02,759
human preference learning: the Bradley-Terry model.

18
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:07,445
This model assumes there is an unobserved, latent reward function, r.

19
00:01:07,445 --> 00:01:09,575
When presented with a prompt,

20
00:01:09,576 --> 00:01:11,706
x, and two candidate responses,

21
00:01:11,706 --> 00:01:14,688
y_w and y_l, the probability that a

22
00:01:14,688 --> 00:01:17,670
human prefers y_w over y_l is modeled

23
00:01:17,670 --> 00:01:22,355
using the sigmoid function of the difference between their respective rewards.

24
00:01:22,355 --> 00:01:25,337
This means that a response with a

25
00:01:25,337 --> 00:01:29,171
higher reward is exponentially more likely to be preferred.

26
00:01:29,171 --> 00:01:32,153
Standard RLHF uses this formulation to train

27
00:01:32,153 --> 00:01:35,135
the reward model via maximum likelihood estimation.

28
00:01:35,135 --> 00:01:38,117
But what if we could mathematically rewrite

29
00:01:38,117 --> 00:01:41,951
this relation to avoid training a reward model altogether?

30
00:01:41,951 --> 00:01:44,300
Direct Preference Optimization, or DPO,

31
00:01:44,300 --> 00:01:47,588
achieves this through an elegant mathematical substitution.

32
00:01:47,588 --> 00:01:50,406
Under the standard RL optimization objective,

33
00:01:50,406 --> 00:01:53,694
which maximizes reward while penalizing deviation from

34
00:01:53,694 --> 00:01:56,513
the reference policy via Kullback-Leibler divergence,

35
00:01:56,513 --> 00:01:59,331
there exists a closed-form analytical solution.

36
00:01:59,331 --> 00:02:02,619
This identity expresses the optimal reward function

37
00:02:02,619 --> 00:02:05,437
in terms of the optimal policy,

38
00:02:05,437 --> 00:02:10,604
the reference policy, and an intractable partition function, Z of x.

39
00:02:10,604 --> 00:02:13,892
Crucially, when we substitute this mathematical identity

40
00:02:13,892 --> 00:02:16,710
back into the Bradley-Terry preference model,

41
00:02:16,710 --> 00:02:21,408
the complex partition function, Z of x, cancels out entirely!

42
00:02:21,407 --> 00:02:24,695
This is the core breakthrough of DPO.

43
00:02:24,695 --> 00:02:27,984
We can express the human preference probability

44
00:02:27,983 --> 00:02:31,271
directly in terms of policy likelihood ratios.

45
00:02:31,271 --> 00:02:33,779
By eliminating the latent reward term,

46
00:02:33,779 --> 00:02:37,541
DPO derives a simple, closed-form binary cross-entropy loss function.

47
00:02:37,541 --> 00:02:41,720
The DPO loss is optimized directly over the policy parameters,

48
00:02:41,720 --> 00:02:45,064
theta, relative to the reference policy, theta ref.

49
00:02:45,064 --> 00:02:47,989
The loss is computed as the negative

50
00:02:47,989 --> 00:02:50,497
expectation over preferred and dispreferred pairs,

51
00:02:50,497 --> 00:02:53,423
of the log sigmoid of beta times

52
00:02:53,423 --> 00:02:56,348
the log ratio of the policy ratios.

53
00:02:56,348 --> 00:02:59,274
In essence, the loss increases when the

54
00:02:59,274 --> 00:03:02,199
policy assigns a higher probability to the

55
00:03:02,199 --> 00:03:05,125
preferred response relative to the reference policy,

56
00:03:05,125 --> 00:03:08,051
and decreases it for the dispreferred response.

57
00:03:08,051 --> 00:03:10,976
The gradient of this loss function acts

58
00:03:10,976 --> 00:03:13,066
as a dynamic vector field,

59
00:03:13,066 --> 00:03:17,664
scaling updates based on how incorrect the model's current preferences are.

60
00:03:17,663 --> 00:03:21,777
DPO represents a massive leap forward in model alignment.

61
00:03:21,777 --> 00:03:26,348
By eliminating the reward model and the unstable PPO loop,

62
00:03:26,348 --> 00:03:28,634
DPO reduces GPU memory requirements,

63
00:03:28,634 --> 00:03:31,833
cuts training times by more than half,

64
00:03:31,833 --> 00:03:36,404
and removes the need for complex reinforcement learning hyper-parameter tuning.

65
00:03:36,404 --> 00:03:39,604
This direct optimization technique is now a

66
00:03:39,604 --> 00:03:44,632
standard pillar in aligning state-of-the-art models like Llama, Mistral, and Gemma.

67
00:03:44,632 --> 00:03:47,831
For more deep dives into the elegant

68
00:03:47,831 --> 00:03:51,031
mathematics and hardware mechanics driving modern AI,

69
00:03:51,031 --> 00:03:54,688
subscribe to Gemini three point five Flash Model.

70
00:03:54,688 --> 00:03:57,887
Let's keep optimizing the future of computation.
